04796nam a22006375i 9781526147851DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97815261478517 a10.7765/97815261478512doi  a(DE-B1597)660564  a(OCoLC)1222778685  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB 7aLIT0240402bisacsh04a809.93352968  aEC 5178qDE-24/21sred2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/20599:120231 aGinger, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInstead of modernity :bThe Western canon and the incorporation of the Hispanic (c. 1850–75) /cAndrew Ginger. 1aManchester : bManchester University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource :b15 black & white illustrations, 20 colour illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInterventions: Rethinking the Nineteenth Century00tFront matter -- tDedication -- tContents -- tList of illustrations -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbreviations and conventions -- tIntroduction -- t1 Meeting -- t2 Departure -- t3 Sacrifice -- t4 Repose -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen all that was solid melted into air. For decades, intellectuals from Benjamin to Bourdieu, Berman to Foucault, have been in thrall to this vision of the mid-nineteenth century. It shaped and underpinned their most influential thoughts, its legacy insinuated into institutionalized theories of culture. In this new book, that vision implodes, as if in a cultural supernova, its exceptionalism and limitations exposed. The story of modernity fades before a spectacle of linkages, stretching from and into the depths of history, the breadths of place. And, in a parallel substitution, the vast territories of the former Spanish Empire’s thread through the narrative, rather than lurking on the peripheries, no longer just the fallen founders of modernity. Instead of modernity goes to the very heart of comparative cultural study: the question of what happens when intimate, dynamic connections are made over place and time, what it is to feel at home amid the lavish diversity of culture. This ambitious interdisciplinary book reconsiders foundational figures of the modern western canon, from Darwin to Cameron, Baudelaire to Whistler. It weaves together brain images from France, preserved insects from the Americas, glass in London, poetry from Argentina, paintings from Spain. Flaubert, Whitman, and Nietzsche find themselves with Hostos from Puerto Rico and Gorriti from Argentina. The flotsam and jetsam of history – optical toys from Madrid – sit with Melville and Marx. The book ranges over theoretical fields: trauma and sexuality studies, theories of visuality, the philosophy of sacrifice and intimacy, the thought of Wittgenstein. Instead of modernity is an adventure in the practice of comparative writing: resonances join suggestively over place and time, the textures of words, phrases and images combine to form moods. This book will be of interest to anyone concerned with the question of modernity and with the fate of cultural theory and comparison.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivilization, Modern, in literature. 0aHispanic Americans in literature. 0aLiterature, Moderny19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterature Studies 2021. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 19th Century .2bisacsh  aHispanic.  aIntimacy.  aModern.  aModernity.  aSpain.  aSpanish.  aWestern canon.1 aGinger, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526147851423Coveru